---
/**
 * HomeEnHalls — 4 exhibition halls in English narrative
 *
 * Used by en/ja/ko/es/fr index.astro via home.template.astro conditional render.
 * 5 langs all share the same English prose (only URL prefix differs).
 *
 * 2026-05-03 sleepy-colden P2 unification — extract from src/pages/en/index.astro.
 */
interface PickArticle {
  title: string;
  href: string;
  footnotes: number;
  readingTime: number;
  description: string;
  featured?: boolean;
}

interface Props {
  topPicks: Record<string, PickArticle[]>;
  langUrlPrefix: string;
}

const { topPicks, langUrlPrefix } = Astro.props;
---

<>
  {/* ── Hall I: What this island looks like ── */}
  <div class="exhibition-hall">
    <div class="hall-divider">
      <div class="hall-line"></div>
      <span class="hall-label">I — What this island looks like</span>
      <div class="hall-line"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="hall-body">
      <p>
        Just 36,000 square kilometers, yet the Philippine Sea Plate pushes into
        the Eurasian Plate at 8 cm a year, making Taiwan one of the most
        mountainous islands on Earth.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/geography`} class="topic-pill"
          >🗺️ The geography here</a
        >
        isn't a postcard — it's an island still growing taller. The Tropic of Cancer
        crosses Chiayi; on the same day you can drive from Kenting's tropical beach
        to Hehuan Mountain's frost.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.geography && topPicks.geography.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.geography.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }

      <p>
        On an island smaller than the Netherlands, 59,000 species crowd together
        — 2.5% of global biodiversity. The Formosan landlocked salmon has
        survived 15,000 years in Dajia Creek; fewer than 600 Formosan black
        bears remain.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/nature`} class="topic-pill"
          >🌿 Taiwan's nature</a
        > vertically compresses every ecosystem from the equator to the subarctic
        — coral reefs to cloud forests in 3,000 meters. A paradise for ecologists,
        a frontline for development pressure.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.nature && topPicks.nature.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.nature.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }

      <p>
        13,000 convenience stores — one for every 2,000 people. Pay bills, pick
        up packages, buy train tickets, photocopy your thesis, all at the same
        counter.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/lifestyle`} class="topic-pill"
          >🏠 Taiwanese life</a
        > is wrapped in hyper-compressed infrastructure — but step into an alley after
        work, and grandma will still ask, "Have you eaten yet?"
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.lifestyle && topPicks.lifestyle.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.lifestyle.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }
    </div>
  </div>

  {/* ── Hall II: How this island came to be ── */}
  <div class="exhibition-hall">
    <div class="hall-divider">
      <div class="hall-line"></div>
      <span class="hall-label">II — How this island came to be</span>
      <div class="hall-line"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="hall-body">
      <p>
        In 1624, the Dutch built Fort Zeelandia in Tainan. Eight regimes
        followed in four centuries — one every fifty years on average — each
        bringing new languages, laws, and time zones.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/history`} class="topic-pill"
          >📜 Taiwan's history</a
        >'s most astonishing chapter came in 1996: 14.3 million people walked
        into polling stations and cast the first direct presidential vote in
        Chinese-speaking history. No bloodshed, no coup. An island under
        authoritarian rule for 38 years quietly turned itself into a democracy.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.history && topPicks.history.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.history.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }

      <p>
        Sixteen indigenous peoples have lived here for 6,000 years. Hoklo
        brought Mazu, Hakka brought Yimin Ye, mainlanders brought Shandong
        mantou from military villages, Southeast Asian immigrants brought Eid
        al-Fitr.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/culture`} class="topic-pill"
          >🎭 Taiwan's culture</a
        > is not a melting pot — nobody got melted. The Dajia Mazu pilgrimage draws
        a million walkers over nine days; the Tsou Mayasvi war ritual happens in Alishan
        the same month. Both are Taiwan, and they don't contradict.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.culture && topPicks.culture.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.culture.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }

      <p>
        On May 17, 2019, the legislature voted to legalize same-sex marriage —
        making Taiwan the first in Asia. Six months earlier, 7.65 million people
        had just voted against it in a referendum.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/society`} class="topic-pill"
          >⚖️ Taiwan's society</a
        >'s most fascinating quality is right here: the referendum said no, the
        legislature said yes, and society kept functioning. People finished
        arguing, then stood in line together for breakfast.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.society && topPicks.society.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.society.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }
    </div>
  </div>

  {/* ── Hall III: What the people are doing ── */}
  <div class="exhibition-hall">
    <div class="hall-divider">
      <div class="hall-line"></div>
      <span class="hall-label">III — What the people are doing</span>
      <div class="hall-line"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="hall-body">
      <p>
        Yan Chang-shou delivered mail at American Express at 23, became general
        manager five years later. Jeremy Lin sat on the bench for two years,
        then rewrote the NBA's Asian narrative in one week. Chen Shu-chu sold
        vegetables at Taitung market for 48 years and donated over NT$10
        million.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/people`} class="topic-pill"
          >👥 Taiwan's people</a
        >
        didn't walk out of textbooks — their stories are worth reading because every
        turning point could have not happened.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.people && topPicks.people.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.people.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }

      <p>
        In 2009, Cai Guo-Qiang detonated nine gunpowder explosions at Taipei
        Fine Arts Museum. The same year, Lin Hwai-min's Cloud Gate Dance Theatre
        rose from the ashes of their Bali studio fire.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/art`} class="topic-pill">🎨 Taiwan's art</a> runs
        from temple Eight Generals face paint to the Venice Biennale, from Jiaozhi
        pottery to digital installations. The question Taiwan's creators ask most
        often isn't "what is beauty" — it's "who are we."
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.art && topPicks.art.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.art.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }

      <p>
        In 1932, Deng Yu-xian wrote "Longing for Spring Wind" — ninety years
        later it's still a KTV regular. The Bunun's pasibutbut (eight-part
        polyphony) caught UNESCO's attention because Western music theory can't
        explain it.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/music`} class="topic-pill"
          >🎵 Taiwan's sound</a
        > runs from tribal chants to Mayday filling an arena with 100,000 voices.
        Music on this island isn't just entertainment — it's how each generation recognizes
        itself.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.music && topPicks.music.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.music.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }
    </div>
  </div>

  {/* ── Hall IV: Where this island is going ── */}
  <div class="exhibition-hall">
    <div class="hall-divider">
      <div class="hall-line"></div>
      <span class="hall-label">IV — Where this island is going</span>
      <div class="hall-line"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="hall-body">
      <p>
        90% of the world's advanced chips ship from Taiwan. A single TSMC fab
        costs US$20 billion; its cleanrooms are 10,000 times cleaner than
        operating theaters.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/technology`} class="topic-pill"
          >💻 This tech island</a
        >
        started from tin-roof workshops in the 1980s Hsinchu Science Park and became,
        forty years later, a supply-chain node that no phone, laptop, or car on Earth
        can bypass. The trade-off: semiconductors consume 7% of Taiwan's total electricity
        — and rising.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.technology && topPicks.technology.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.technology.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }

      <p>
        In 1960, Taiwan's GDP per capita was US$154 — lower than the Congo's.
        Sixty years later it exceeds US$33,000, without oil, colonial dividends,
        or continental hinterland.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/economy`} class="topic-pill"
          >📈 Taiwan's economy</a
        >
        is the story of a resource-poor island turning itself into a global supply-chain
        hub. The method was singular: work harder and pivot faster than everyone else.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.economy && topPicks.economy.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.economy.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }

      <p>
        A bowl of beef noodle soup: Sichuan red-braised base, Taiwanese soy
        sweetness, and a 1949 veteran's homesickness. Bubble tea left a Taichung
        tea house and landed on five continents.
        <a href={`${langUrlPrefix}/food`} class="topic-pill"
          >🍜 Taiwan's flavor</a
        >
        is its immigration history — Hoklo oyster omelets, Hakka ginger intestines,
        indigenous millet wine, new immigrant fish sauce. Four centuries of homesickness,
        all simmering in the same night market.
      </p>
      {
        topPicks.food && topPicks.food.length > 0 && (
          <div class="hall-picks">
            {topPicks.food.map((a) => (
              <a href={a.href} class="pick-card">
                <span class="pick-head">
                  <span class="pick-title">{a.title}</span>
                  <span class="pick-fn">{a.footnotes} sources</span>
                </span>
                {a.description && (
                  <span class="pick-desc">
                    {a.description.length > 80
                      ? a.description.slice(0, 77) + '...'
                      : a.description}
                  </span>
                )}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        )
      }
    </div>
  </div>
</>
